\f3\i\b \cf0 Eibar, Eber
\f2\i0\b0 \
Eibar is the most pervasive language of the 
\f4\i huum
\f2\i0  population, spoken by virtually all 
\f4\i huum
\f2\i0  residents of Saskantinon, as well as most others 
\f4\i sints
\f2\i0  north of the 
\f4\i Settan
\f2\i0  River.\
\
Eibar is the language of power in the Saskan region. It is the official language of the two major 
\f4\i huum
\f2\i0 -centric political federations -- the 
\f4\i Borded
\f2\i0  Federation, and the federated and associated provinces of the 
\f4\i Fatunikan Dominion. 
\f2\i0 It is the canonical language of the Noonday Scribes of 
\f4\i Fatunika
\f2\i0 , who exert a strong ideological presence.  \
\
In the the 
\f4\i Kahila
\f2\i0  lands and in the
\f4\i  
\f2\i0 Runes of Bye
\f4\i , 
\f2\i0 provinces
\f4\i  
\f2\i0 which are only loosely associated with the 
\f4\i Fatunikan Dominion
\f2\i0 , Eibar is widely understood and used but 
\f4\i Sogomsh
\f2\i0  is more pervasive in daily usage. The Magisters of Byenung are renowned for their expertise with spoken and written Eibar. \
\
The pronunciation of Eibar as it is spoken in the province of Eibar is considered to be the oldest and hence most "proper" spoken form. Eibar province, near the mouth of the 
\f4\i Pavan
\f2\i0  River, was the earliest settlement of 
\f4\i Bar
\f2\i0 -speaking 
\f4\i huum
\f2\i0  in the region adhering closely to the 
\f4\i Fatunikan
\f2\i0  dogma.  As the centuries passed, the Eibar language diversified as the 
\f4\i huum
\f2\i0  population spread and immigrants arrived from Wesshewen, Ilyushan, Krbshanana, Aranzen and other lands even further away.  Along with multiple 
\f4\i Bar
\f2\i0  languages, a wide variety of local Eibar accents, in some cases verging on dialects, developed as well. \
\
"Old Eibar", as the "proper" form is called, is particularly characteristic of three important organizations: the Noonday Scribes, the Byenung Magisters and the Council of the Eibarfolk.\
\
All Eibar-speaking areas of Saskantinon sport regional accents.  In most cases they consist of minor variations in vowel sounds and a few idiomatic words. Those closest to being full-fledged dialects are spoken in the western provinces, especially in the remote hills and valleys of Eelan and the High Weir Lands, and in the remote northern plains of Oaknott, Norgyte and Sungyte.
